## 4) Final Java Code & Learning Pattern (Full Content)

```java
import java.util.*;

class Result {

    public static long getNumberOfDroppedCases(List<List<Integer>> requests, int maxCases, int rate) {
        requests.sort(Comparator.comparingInt(event -> event.get(0)));

        long queueSize = 0L;
        long droppedCases = 0L;
        long previousTime = requests.get(0).get(0);

        for (List<Integer> request : requests) {
            long currentTime = request.get(0);
            long incomingCases = request.get(1);

            long elapsed = currentTime - previousTime;
            queueSize = Math.max(0L, queueSize - elapsed * rate);

            queueSize += incomingCases;
            if (queueSize > maxCases) {
                droppedCases += queueSize - maxCases;
                queueSize = maxCases;
            }

            previousTime = currentTime;
        }

        return droppedCases;
    }
}
```

Learning Pattern:
- In queue systems with fixed drain rate and sparse events, jump directly across time gaps.

## 5) Complexity Analysis

- Time Complexity: $O(n \log n)$ due to sorting
- Space Complexity: $O(1)$ extra (excluding sort internals)

